body:
Everything starts with childhood…

So, I’ve said before that I just thought Captain Marvel was a good film in a series of great films. But it didn’t really matter because, clearly, the film meant way more than that to so many other people.

Of course, you have people saying that if a film is really going to push a feminist angle (which, let’s be honest here, CM is. It is very much a feminist movie), then it has to be better than ‘Just sort of good’ or 'Meh’. Or that successful female superhero movies like Wonder Woman or (bit of a stretch) Aelita makes defending Captain Marvel null and void because 'Well, these feminist movies were successful, so clearly people are making a big deal over nothing!’

Let me tell you why that’s bullshit.

Feminism, like everything, starts with childhood.

The feminist ideal, in my very much male mind at least, is seeing a little girl walking up to a group of boys and asking to play superheroes with them.

And when one boy inevitably says 'No, you can’t cause your a girl’, that girl will respond with 'BITCH, I’M WONDER WOMAN!’

Best case scenario: The boys let her play and another girl wants to come in. They ask her who she wants to be.

Well, clearly Wonder Woman, right? After all, she’s a successful female superhero and thus the only one we need, right?

No, sorry, not all little girls can be Wonder Woman. Not all little girls WANT to be Wonder Woman. But some little girls might want to be Black Widow. Some might want to be Scarlet Witch. Some might want to be Spider-Girl. Some might want to be Supergirl, or Batwoman, or Black Canary, or Star-Girl, or Kate Bishop, or Jessica Cruz, or X-23, or Storm, or Shadowcat, or Rogue.

One might want to be Squirrel Girl. And that little girl would be awesome.

But, inevitably, one girl will come up and says she wants to be Captain Marvel. And if one boy asks why since her movie was so 'boring’, she should have every right to say:

'I just think she’s cool.’

Because the average little boy doesn’t put much more thought than that over which superhero they want to be.

I certainly didn’t whenever I pretended to be a Power Ranger.

The reason why this is important is, as I said before, everything starts in childhood. Little boys playing with little girls as equals, with equal amounts of options to choose from, will lead to adult boys and girls 'playing’ as equals.

So, barring an absolutely trash feminist movie, that completely misses the whole point of feminism, it really does not and should not matter what the quality of the movie is. Because at this point, women are just trying to catch up with the sheer, unending options men have over which superheroes they’re kids can pretend to be. It can be forgiven if one of their movies is just sort of 'meh’.

Because, as I said before, it wasn’t made for us. It was made for them.

…

This can pretty much be as metaphorical as you want to make it.

title: 'Captain Marvel' (2019) Flew Faster, Further and Higher than Anyone Anticipated
body:
‘Captain Marvel’ (2019) Flew Faster, Further and Higher than Anyone Anticipated

Having waited my whole life to see Captain Marvel on the silver screen, unlike most comic fans, I was not disappointed. But I need to explain some things before we talk about Brie Larson in the titular role of Captain Marvel (2019).

Yes, I was a little sad it was not the original comic character created by Stan Lee and Gene Colanin Marvel Super-Heroes #12 (December 1967). He was an alien…
